The Nyeri government has bought Sh4 million survey and mapping equipment from Germany.Lands executive Robert Thuo on Tuesday said the equipment will cut costs. The government had hired a consultancy firm to carry out surveys. &ldquo;The equipment will use modern technology to solve land disputes. The equipment being used previously was obsolete,&rdquo; he said.Thuo said more surveyors will be hired to map out 220 villages. &ldquo;Six of the villages have already been surveyed. The county is working to solve land disputes and plan towns,&rdquo; he said.Thuo said the modern equipment will fast-track the resolution of land disputes. &ldquo;A survey that previously took one week to be completed is now being done in half a day,&rdquo; he said.